{"slug": "seer", "root": "seer", "category": "divination", "gloss": "one who sees the hidden", "definition": "A seer is one who sees the hidden — a beholder of visions and futures. It is the plainest word in the whole divination family, describing the diviner by the bare act of sight; where a *sibyl* is a titled prophetess and a *soothsayer* a truth-teller, the seer simply, and homely, sees.", "history": "The word is homegrown: Old English *sēon*, 'to see', plus the agent ending *-er*, standing among a crowd of borrowed Greco-Latin *-mancers*. Its sense is the oldest kind of knowing — an Irish tale calls its seer a *fissid*, 'one who knows' (Page and Rider, *The Routledge History of Medieval Magic*), and myth gave the gift most memorably to Tiresias, the blind seer (Ginzburg, *Ecstasies*). In the crystal-gazing of the Renaissance the seer became a working role: John Dee begged God for 'a good seer, and skryer of spirituall apparitions' (Page, *Magic in the Cloister*), the one who watched the glass while the magician read the book.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Sophie Page & Catherine Rider (eds.), The Routledge History of Medieval Magic", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Sophie Page, Magic in the Cloister", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Carlo Ginzburg, Ecstasies: Deciphering the Witches' Sabbath", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)"}], "commentary": null, "commentary_sources": [], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"lang": "Old English", "origin": "Old English sēon 'to see' + -er", "first": "c. 1300", "note": "The plainest word in the whole divination family — just 'one who sees' — standing among a crowd of borrowed Greco-Latin -mancers.", "hook": "The homegrown English prophet among the Greek imports."}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 23